Intended learning outcomesOn completion of this subject students should
Construct rigorous mathematical proofs, including proofs by contradiction, contraposition, and induction;
Apply the field and order axioms to prove facts about real numbers;
Use the epsilon-delta proofs both as a theoretical tool and a tool of approximation;
Discuss the relationship between the properties of a sequence and whether the sequence converges;
Articulate and apply the theory of continuous and differentiable functions;
Interpret the integral of piecewise continuous functions as a limit of Riemann sums and derive basic properties of the integral from this construction;
Determine the convergence and divergence of infinite series and improper integrals;
Demonstrate a good knowledge of the theory and practice of power series expansions and Taylor polynomial approximations; and
Describe the role of Fourier series in representing periodic functions.

